<subSubSection pageId="124" pageNumber="125" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="124" pageNumber="125">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1830" class="Hexapoda" family="Rhysodidae" genus="Clinidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Clinidium</taxonomicName>
Kirby, 1830: 6. Type species: 
<taxonomicName class="Hexapoda" family="Rhysodidae" genus="Clinidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guildingii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Clinidium guildingii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Kirby, 1830 by monotypy. Etymology (original). From the Greek 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">clinidion</emphasis>
(small couch), alluding to the body shape of the adult [neuter].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="124" pageNumber="125" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="124" pageNumber="125">
About 75 species in the Nearctic (six species), Neotropical (about 65 species), and Palaearctic (three species) Regions arrayed in four subgenera: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R.T. Bell" authorityYear="1970" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Arctoclinidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Arctoclinidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(nine species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kirby" authorityYear="1830" class="Hexapoda" family="Rhysodidae" genus="Clinidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Clinidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
s.str. (about 50 Neotropical species), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell &amp; Bell" authorityYear="1978" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Mexiclinidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Mexiclinidium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bell and Bell (11 Middle American species), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bell &amp; Bell" authorityYear="1978" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Tainoa" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="124" pageNumber="125" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Tainoa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Bell and Bell (four West Indian species).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="124" pageNumber="125" type="identification">
<paragraph pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="124" pageNumber="125">Bell and Bell (1985) revised the species of the world and provided keys for their identification.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
